Class PolicyChangeBuilder

  • java.lang.Object
    • gw.api.databuilder.DataBuilder<PolicyPeriod,B>

  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    ExtendedMultiQuoteJobBuilder, IMultiQuoteJobBuilder, ValueGenerator<PolicyPeriod>
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    MultiQuotePolicyChangeBuilder

    public class PolicyChangeBuilder
extends NonSubmissionJobBuilder<PolicyChangeBuilder>
implements ExtendedMultiQuoteJobBuilder
    Builder for a PolicyChange job. Simple usage is 
       new PolicyChangeBuilder(basedOnPeriod).withEffectiveDate(date).createAndCommit()
    but this immediately creates a BOUND policy change, which means its policy graph won't be any different than its basedOn. If you need a change to the policy, a more common scenario is 
       var builder = new PolicyChangeBuilder(basedOnPeriod).withEffectiveDate(date).isDraft()
   var change = builder.create()
   ...change some thing(s) on the policy...
   builder.requestQuote()
   builder.bind()
   change.Bundle.commit()

      • PolicyChangeBuilder

        public PolicyChangeBuilder()

        Create a PolicyChangeBuilder with EffectiveTimeFromPlugin=true and Status=BOUND.

        The populators for this builder run at POSTPROCESS_PRIORITY_1 and POSTPROCESS_PRIORITY_2. The PRIORITY_1 populator is responsible for setting the period dates and secondaryNamedInsured; the one at PRIORITY_2 handles producerCode and Status (including quoting, binding and withdrawing as necessary).

      • withEffectiveTimeFromPlugin

        public PolicyChangeBuilder withEffectiveTimeFromPlugin(boolean effectiveTimeFromPlugin)

        Whether to build a policy change whose effective date's time component is determined by the installed EffectiveTimePlugin. If false, the effectiveDate will be used as-is. Default is true.

        For policy change jobs, the effective time plugin is called before the job is started (in StartPolicyChange.pcf), so in general, this builder needs to call the plugin to mimic that behavior.
